quran[24]{c,v,t}:
  18,51,"I did not make them witnesses of the creation of the heavens and the earth, nor of the creation of themselves, nor did I take those who lead astray for my supporters"
  18,52,"On the day when He shall say, 'Call ye my partners whom ye pretend:' and they shall call on them, but they shall not answer them; and we will set the vale of perdition between them"
  18,53,"and the sinners shall see the fire, and shall think that they are going to fall therein, and shall find no escape therefrom"
  18,54,We have turned about in this Qur'an for men every parable; but man is ever at most things a caviller
  18,55,"Naught prevented men from believing when the guidance came to them, or from asking pardon of their Lord, except the coming on them of the course of those of yore, or the coming of the torment before their eyes"
  18,56,We sent not prophets save as heralds of glad tidings and as warners; but those who misbelieve wrangle with vain speech to make void the truth therewith; and they take my signs and the warnings given them as a jest
  18,57,"Who is more unjust than he who, being reminded of the signs of his Lord, turns away therefrom, and forgets what his hands have done before? verily, we will place veils upon their hearts lest they should understand, and dullness in their ears! And if thou shouldst call them to the guidance, they will not be guided then for ever"
  18,58,"But thy Lord is forgiving, endowed with mercy; were He to punish them for what they have earned He would have hastened for them the torment. Nay rather, they have their appointed time, and shall never find a refuge beside Him"
  18,59,"These cities, we destroyed them when they were unjust; and for their destruction we set an appointed time"
  18,60,"And when Moses said to his servant, 'I will not cease until I reach the confluence of the two seas, or else I will go on for years"
  18,61,"But when they reached the confluence of the two they forgot their fish, and it took its way in the sea with a free course"
  18,62,"And when they had passed by, he said to his servant, 'Bring us our dinners, for we have met with toil from this journey of ours"
  18,63,"Said he, 'What thinkest thou? when we resorted to the rock, then, verily, I forgot the fish, but it was only Satan who made me forget it, lest I should remember it; and it took its way in the set wondrously"
  18,64,"Said he, 'This is what we were searching for.' So they turned back upon their footsteps, following them up"
  18,65,"Then they found a servant of our servants, to whom we had given mercy from ourselves, and had taught him knowledge from before us"
  18,66,"Said Moses to him, 'Shall I follow thee, so that thou mayest teach me, from what thou hast been taught, the right way"
  18,67,"said he, 'Verily, thou canst never have patience with me"
  18,68,How canst thou be patient in what thou comprehendest no knowledge of
  18,69,"He said, 'Thou wilt find me, if God will, patient; nor will I rebel against thy bidding"
  18,70,"He said, 'Then, if thou followest me, ask me not about anything until I begin for them the mention of it"
  18,71,"So they set out until when they rode in the bark, he scuttled it. Said he, 'Hast thou scuttled it to drown its crew? Thou hast produced a strange thing"
  18,72,"Said he, 'Did I not tell thee, verily, thou canst never have patience with me"
  18,73,"Said he, 'Rebuke me not for forgetting, and impose not on me a difficult command"
  18,74,"So they set out until they met a boy, and he killed him. And he (Moses) said, 'Hast thou killed a pure person without (his killing) a person? thou hast produced an unheard-of thing"